            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Sharon Gibson\u2019s story is woven into the fog-laced streets of San Francisco\u2019s less-glamorous neighborhoods. Born in the Richmond District to Cantonese immigrants, she grew up in the back of her family\u2019s small laundromat. Her parents, who worked relentlessly, envisioned a future for their daughter in a stable, high-paying profession like medicine. But Sharon was drawn to the people on the margins\u2014the elderly neighbors who struggled with English, the kids who had nowhere to go after school. This deep-seated empathy led her to SF State, where she pursued a Bachelor's in Social Work, a choice that quietly disappointed her parents but set the course for her life.\n\nHer early career was spent in the trenches as a caseworker, navigating the city\u2019s complex bureaucracy to secure housing and aid for vulnerable families. It was during this time she met Mark Gibson, a kind, dedicated public defender who shared her passion for social justice. They married and settled into a rent-controlled apartment in Noe Valley, building a life centered on shared values, community potlucks, and long walks through the city.\n\nThe major turning point in Sharon\u2019s life was Mark\u2019s sudden death from a heart attack twelve years ago. The loss was profound, but instead of retreating, Sharon poured her energy into her work with renewed focus. She climbed the ranks through sheer competence and dedication, eventually becoming the Program Director for a non-profit serving at-risk youth.\n\nNow at 53, Sharon\u2019s life has a quiet, purposeful rhythm. She still lives in the same Noe Valley apartment, its walls filled with photos of Mark and art from local street fairs. Her 2.5-mile commute on the J-Church MUNI line is a daily ritual, a time to observe the city she has spent her life serving. Her days are long, filled with managing budgets, mentoring staff, and fighting for funding. Her six-figure salary provides stability, but her wealth is measured in the lives she impacts. Her dream isn\u2019t retirement, but to launch a sustainable mentorship program that will continue long after she\u2019s gone, a lasting legacy in the city that is both her home and her life's work."
